from &quot;A TRIP TO THE FAR WEST&quot;, <i>Bell’s Life in Sydney and Sporting Reviewer</i>, Saturday 12 February 1848, p. 1 [3rd column, 3rd paragraph]:

<blockquote>That is what they call the &quot;Soldier's Pinch,&quot; why or wherefore I cannot tell, but the reason commonly assigned is this: - A soldier - more probably some one known by the nick-name of The Soldier - was travelling with a heavily laden dray; in going up that <i>pinch</i> - an ugly one it is too - the driver requested him &quot;to block up;&quot; the poor man having no block to <i>block up</i> with, he put his foot behind the wheel, which immediately pinched it clean off; that is the reason why it has got such a strange name.</blockquote>

- <a href="http://trove.nla.gov.au/ndp/del/article/59767182" rel="nofollow">trove.nla.gov.au/ndp/del/article/59767182</a>

